00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:27.210
AUDIENCE: Yeah, right.

00:46:27.210 --> 00:46:28.420
FLOYD ABRAMS: Which
is what they did.

00:46:28.420 --> 00:46:31.620
No, but on a privacy basis,
I agree with you.

00:46:31.620 --> 00:46:37.910
And look, one of the realities
these days, these years, and

00:46:37.910 --> 00:46:42.260
well into the future so far as
we can see, is that people are

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:47.290
saying so much about themselves
online and

00:46:47.290 --> 00:46:54.210
otherwise that willingly or not,
or thoughtfully or not,

00:46:54.210 --> 00:46:55.570
they're giving up.

00:46:55.570 --> 00:47:00.960
They're choosing to give up,
in a sense, their privacy.

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:05.980
I mean if you write something
down and send it out and don't

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:11.380
find some effective way of
concealing who you are, it's

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:12.860
your problem.

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:15.060
AUDIENCE: And if I could just
ask one follow up question on

00:47:15.060 --> 00:47:18.030
a different subject about the
question of leaks by the

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:18.510
government.

00:47:18.510 --> 00:47:19.870
FLOYD ABRAMS: Yeah.

00:47:19.870 --> 00:47:23.500
AUDIENCE: So you know, my sense
is that you agree that

00:47:23.500 --> 00:47:26.160
it can't be stopped
at this point.

00:47:26.160 --> 00:47:30.370
It's essentially become a policy
tool for whichever

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:34.060
administration is in power in
order to push the political

00:47:34.060 --> 00:47:37.170
debate one way or the other,
or influence Congress, or

00:47:37.170 --> 00:47:38.640
influence the public.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:40.620
But I wonder--

00:47:40.620 --> 00:47:41.750
I'll speak for myself--

00:47:41.750 --> 00:47:44.590
I feel like there's a really
corrosive effect there.

00:47:44.590 --> 00:47:47.490
And the best example I can think
of is the lead up to the

00:47:47.490 --> 00:47:51.900
Iraq War, where it turned out
that the administration was

00:47:51.900 --> 00:47:56.610
feeding the New York Times
information and then quoting

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:59.680
the information that it had been
fed on the Sunday talk

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:01.730
shows in order to say, well
look, it was published in the

00:48:01.730 --> 00:48:02.540
New York Times.

00:48:02.540 --> 00:48:03.190
This was true.

00:48:03.190 --> 00:48:05.780
And so it seems like it's
one thing to say,

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:06.970
OK, we're going to--

00:48:06.970 --> 00:48:09.490
any government, doesn't matter
whether it's Democratic or

00:48:09.490 --> 00:48:11.390
Republican, it's one thing to
say we're going to leak

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:14.760
because we want to push public
policy one way or another.

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:18.370
But it's something else then
to implicate the newspapers

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:21.690
directly as a sort of a
policy making tool.

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:24.510
And I just wonder what
you think about that.

00:48:24.510 --> 00:48:28.390
FLOYD ABRAMS: I agree.

00:48:28.390 --> 00:48:31.370
And as you said by way of
introduction, there's not a

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:34.130
legal comment, and your question
wasn't about the law.

00:48:38.970 --> 00:48:43.782
The Iraqi situation is an
interesting one in some ways.

00:48:43.782 --> 00:48:48.210
I believe that the scientists
who were quoted in those New

00:48:48.210 --> 00:48:51.760
York Times articles believed
what they were saying.

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:56.340
I also think I know that the
reporter who I represented who

00:48:56.340 --> 00:49:01.370
wrote those articles believed
but she was saying.

00:49:01.370 --> 00:49:06.350
But the government certainly, we
know now, was engaged in a

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:13.640
campaign to gather public
support for the war that

00:49:13.640 --> 00:49:17.510
included in the information
they provided were false

00:49:17.510 --> 00:49:18.740
statements.

00:49:18.740 --> 00:49:24.660
Not just proved to be false,
but known to be false.

00:49:24.660 --> 00:49:28.710
And that is unacceptable
behavior.

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:32.940
And your example couldn't
be more on point.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:35.270
They not only leaked the
information, then when it was

00:49:35.270 --> 00:49:38.810
published they said, the New
York Times said, as if they

00:49:38.810 --> 00:49:41.950
had nothing to do with
the information

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:44.450
getting to the Times.

00:49:44.450 --> 00:49:48.900
And that sort of cynicism
it sounds like

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:51.540
the stuff of novels.

00:49:51.540 --> 00:49:53.130
But that's what happened.

00:49:53.130 --> 00:49:57.000
And what can you say other
than it's worthy of

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:57.910
condemnation.

00:49:57.910 --> 00:50:00.770
We hope it doesn't happen, or
we hope if it does happen,

00:50:00.770 --> 00:50:03.580
it's exposed.

00:50:03.580 --> 00:50:05.390
Anyone else?

00:50:05.390 --> 00:50:06.810
Yes.

00:50:06.810 --> 00:50:08.570
Did I see a hand or I see--

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:09.820
yeah?

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:18.130
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:50:18.130 --> 00:50:18.570
FLOYD ABRAMS: Hello.

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:23.090
AUDIENCE: So from what I know,
the First Amendment protects

00:50:23.090 --> 00:50:28.880
citizens against what citizens
say from interference by the

00:50:28.880 --> 00:50:30.600
government.

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:35.090
And I was wondering it still
allows interference by private

00:50:35.090 --> 00:50:37.850
individuals and corporations?

00:50:37.850 --> 00:50:40.220
So what do you think--

00:50:40.220 --> 00:50:41.910
should something change there?

00:50:41.910 --> 00:50:46.830
Should this be allowed or should
it become more strong

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:47.930
in favor of protecting?

00:50:47.930 --> 00:50:50.080
Because it's not only the
government that can threaten

00:50:50.080 --> 00:50:54.550
your speech.

00:50:54.550 --> 00:50:58.710
Increasingly where you write
your comments, where you

00:50:58.710 --> 00:51:01.900
create speech, is owned
not by the government.

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:05.250
It's like a platform
that is online.

00:51:05.250 --> 00:51:09.650
Or like where you're employed,
the employer has some power

00:51:09.650 --> 00:51:13.420
over what you can say, and
you can't control that.

00:51:13.420 --> 00:51:18.630
Should the government have per
se a positive obligation to

00:51:18.630 --> 00:51:22.990
ensure that the citizens have
freedom of expression up to a

00:51:22.990 --> 00:51:30.010
point and ensuring that other
entities do not interfere with

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:31.840
these rights?

00:51:31.840 --> 00:51:34.850
FLOYD ABRAMS: That's a
very, very serious

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:37.400
and powerful question.

00:51:37.400 --> 00:51:40.920
First, simply as a legal matter,
the answer is easier

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:44.660
than the policy question
that you're asking.

00:51:44.660 --> 00:51:49.380
As a legal matter, the Bill of
Rights applies only to the

00:51:49.380 --> 00:51:51.160
government.

00:51:51.160 --> 00:51:55.370
It's even phrased, you know,
Congress shall make no law

00:51:55.370 --> 00:51:58.930
abridging the freedom of
speech or of the press.

00:51:58.930 --> 00:52:02.970
Congress has been expanded to
mean the President and the

00:52:02.970 --> 00:52:05.670
states and the courts,
et cetera.

00:52:05.670 --> 00:52:07.680
But it's all government
entities.

00:52:07.680 --> 00:52:10.600
But your question's a
lot better and more

00:52:10.600 --> 00:52:12.700
interesting than that.

00:52:12.700 --> 00:52:17.440
There are countries that do
protect far more than we do.

00:52:17.440 --> 00:52:22.110
A private speech against
private institutions,

00:52:22.110 --> 00:52:25.990
corporations, employers.

00:52:25.990 --> 00:52:33.960
We are basically a laissez faire
country in general in

00:52:33.960 --> 00:52:36.764
that respect.

00:52:36.764 --> 00:52:39.920
You know, people can say what
they want, and other people

00:52:39.920 --> 00:52:43.620
can hold them accountable, which
is to say they can get

00:52:43.620 --> 00:52:46.300
fired for saying it.

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:48.620
They can be punished, so long
as it's not the government

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:52.380
doing it, for saying it.

00:52:52.380 --> 00:52:57.580
And the question of whether,
putting aside the

00:52:57.580 --> 00:53:04.710
Constitution, whether we think
it's a good idea to, in

00:53:04.710 --> 00:53:09.340
effect, import the government
into that situation by saying

00:53:09.340 --> 00:53:13.440
to the government, why don't
you do something to ensure

00:53:13.440 --> 00:53:19.280
that private speech shall not
be so subject to control or

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:24.860
sanctions or the like by large,
powerful, private

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:26.110
institutions?

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:32.630
My reaction is that I don't
think we should go in that

00:53:32.630 --> 00:53:41.180
direction in part because I
don't trust the government to

00:53:41.180 --> 00:53:46.150
be in effect the decision maker
or even to interfere for

00:53:46.150 --> 00:53:50.350
the good purpose of protecting
more speech.

00:53:50.350 --> 00:53:53.660
But it is a very real issue.

00:53:53.660 --> 00:53:57.300
And for a lot of people in a lot
of situations, it's much

00:53:57.300 --> 00:54:00.430
more real than any of the fights
that I've been talking

00:54:00.430 --> 00:54:04.440
about between the government
and the people or the

00:54:04.440 --> 00:54:09.040
government and the press,
and the like.

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:13.010
One of my concerns
is that there has

00:54:13.010 --> 00:54:14.510
been a tendency abroad--

00:54:14.510 --> 00:54:18.320
one of the things I think we've
learned as a country--

00:54:18.320 --> 00:54:21.760
is that there really is a domino
effect, to use a bad

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:26.410
phrase from a different
generation, when you sort of

00:54:26.410 --> 00:54:33.600
put the government into the role
of helper, assurer, of

00:54:33.600 --> 00:54:37.920
free speech rights is that
there's a great tendency, and

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:41.650
there has been a great tendency
in abroad, to wind up

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:44.270
with the government
in the news room.

00:54:44.270 --> 00:54:48.700
And the government as decision
maker, not just about keeping

00:54:48.700 --> 00:54:52.620
people from keeping other people
from speaking, but in

00:54:52.620 --> 00:54:54.360
other situations.

00:54:54.360 --> 00:54:56.210
But that's just a very
short answer

00:54:56.210 --> 00:54:59.045
to a very hard question.

00:55:02.650 --> 00:55:05.740
This is not a promise, and
there's no reason for you to

00:55:05.740 --> 00:55:09.230
care about what I'm about to
say, but I do owe the Yale

00:55:09.230 --> 00:55:11.890
University Press
one more book.

00:55:11.890 --> 00:55:15.930
And that is something that I've
thought of writing about.

00:55:15.930 --> 00:55:17.180
Yes.

00:55:18.990 --> 00:55:20.220
Oh, sorry.

00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:22.710
AUDIENCE: As technology
continues to develop, we're

00:55:22.710 --> 00:55:24.820
finding more and more
ways to communicate.

00:55:24.820 --> 00:55:30.530
We had landline phones and wire
tap regulations, cell

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:33.550
phones, cordless phones, and now
electronic communications,

00:55:33.550 --> 00:55:36.800
text, texting, online email.

00:55:36.800 --> 00:55:39.160
And these are all mechanisms
of person to person

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:40.390
communication.

00:55:40.390 --> 00:55:43.840
Do you think that technology is
fundamentally changing the

00:55:43.840 --> 00:55:47.930
way that we view and are
given these rights?

00:55:47.930 --> 00:55:51.890
And do you think that's the
right thing to happen?

00:55:51.890 --> 00:55:54.120
FLOYD ABRAMS: I don't have any
doubt that technology is

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:59.380
changing the way we exercise
the rights, and therefore,

00:55:59.380 --> 00:56:04.420
changing our ability to engage
in those rights.

00:56:04.420 --> 00:56:13.630
Also as technology changes the
issues, we'll change, although

00:56:13.630 --> 00:56:18.290
have the same base sort of
characteristics and arguments

00:56:18.290 --> 00:56:21.690
about them, about what the
role of government is in

00:56:21.690 --> 00:56:26.980
assuring fairness, as per
the last question.

00:56:26.980 --> 00:56:29.015
Net neutrality comes up.

00:56:29.015 --> 00:56:36.890
I mean, other ideas are voiced
and placed on the public

00:56:36.890 --> 00:56:45.310
agenda to try to deal with the
reality of new technology.

00:56:45.310 --> 00:56:51.630
I mean, one way it comes up is
simply one where the issue

00:56:51.630 --> 00:56:55.720
then becomes, is there any more
need for this regulation

00:56:55.720 --> 00:56:59.000
or that regulation at all since
there's so much speech

00:56:59.000 --> 00:56:59.750
in this area?

00:56:59.750 --> 00:57:04.710
I did a case for Time Warner
Cable, which is on awaiting a

00:57:04.710 --> 00:57:09.190
decision now, about whether it
is still constitutional under

00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:12.610
the First Amendment for Congress
to have required

00:57:12.610 --> 00:57:17.670
cable companies to carry
networks, basically, that they

00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:19.190
don't want to carry.

00:57:19.190 --> 00:57:22.020
And one of the arguments we made
is, look, there's so much

00:57:22.020 --> 00:57:25.820
speech from so many sources
now, you've

00:57:25.820 --> 00:57:28.420
got to let them go.

00:57:28.420 --> 00:57:32.080
And if not now, later.

00:57:32.080 --> 00:57:38.580
So the changing forms of
technology affects everything.

00:57:38.580 --> 00:57:40.935
It affects privacy, we were
talking about earlier.

00:57:43.640 --> 00:57:48.850
It is even leading to some very
interesting cases in the

00:57:48.850 --> 00:57:50.850
libel area, for example.

00:57:50.850 --> 00:57:56.910
One judge wrote an opinion
basically saying, online

00:57:56.910 --> 00:58:03.780
speech by its nature is not
taken as literally as the

00:58:03.780 --> 00:58:07.330
speech in my book, you know,
with a hard cover on it and

00:58:07.330 --> 00:58:09.930
everything.

00:58:09.930 --> 00:58:11.270
People don't mean it.

00:58:11.270 --> 00:58:13.150
It's more casual.

00:58:13.150 --> 00:58:22.250
It's not take to mean the
ultimate meanings of what one

00:58:22.250 --> 00:58:25.530
might view it if it appeared
in a different medium of

00:58:25.530 --> 00:58:28.060
communication.

00:58:28.060 --> 00:58:31.940
And I don't have any doubt that
we're going to need a lot

00:58:31.940 --> 00:58:37.600
more decisions and a lot more
legal decisions as the

00:58:37.600 --> 00:58:40.300
on-the-ground reality changes.

00:58:40.300 --> 00:58:42.330
And of course the laws
always behind.

00:58:42.330 --> 00:58:46.320
Technology's way ahead of
anything that the law can

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:51.060
handle, or predict or be
ready to deal with.

00:58:51.060 --> 00:58:54.760
And by the time cases come up
to the court, sometimes the

00:58:54.760 --> 00:58:57.920
technology has already changed
to such an extent that the

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:01.950
issue isn't even that
relevant anymore.

00:59:01.950 --> 00:59:08.760
But the thrust of your question
I agree with.

00:59:08.760 --> 00:59:12.390
And we're going to--

00:59:12.390 --> 00:59:16.370
the pace of the change of
technology in this country is

00:59:16.370 --> 00:59:23.520
so great that it is very hard
for the law to keep pace with

00:59:23.520 --> 00:59:31.000
it in terms of even trying to
deal with it, and in a society

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:35.330
where, as I suggested earlier,
that Congress can't agree on

00:59:35.330 --> 00:59:38.700
almost anything anyway.

00:59:38.700 --> 00:59:41.956
It means we'll be sort of even
more laissez faire, as it

00:59:41.956 --> 00:59:43.960
were, for better or worse.

00:59:43.960 --> 00:59:48.620
There will be probably less
regulation for better or worse

00:59:48.620 --> 00:59:51.780
because no one's going to be
able to agree on anything on

00:59:51.780 --> 00:59:53.210
what to do about it.

00:59:53.210 --> 00:59:54.790
Yes.

00:59:54.790 --> 00:59:57.740
AUDIENCE: Is the Constitution
contain protections for a

00:59:57.740 --> 01:00:01.780
journalist who need to
misrepresent themselves while

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:04.510
uncovering facts that they
intend to publish, say, in a

01:00:04.510 --> 01:00:07.260
way that contravenes a contract
that they might sign

01:00:07.260 --> 01:00:09.340
or something like that?

01:00:09.340 --> 01:00:10.750
FLOYD ABRAMS: Well not
to breach a contract

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:13.570
that they sign, no.

01:00:13.570 --> 01:00:25.650
But generally, a journalist who
suggests to someone that

01:00:25.650 --> 01:00:30.120
the article is going to be good
for him is not held to

01:00:30.120 --> 01:00:34.830
that in the courts.

01:00:34.830 --> 01:00:40.210
But there are situations in
which journalists promised

01:00:40.210 --> 01:00:42.230
something, and then the question
is, what should the

01:00:42.230 --> 01:00:43.340
law do about it?

01:00:43.340 --> 01:00:48.490
One really interesting case,
occurred in Minnesota 15,

01:00:48.490 --> 01:00:50.980
maybe 20, years ago.

01:00:50.980 --> 01:00:52.390
Two candidates running for

01:00:52.390 --> 01:00:56.010
lieutenant governor of Minnesota.

01:00:56.010 --> 01:01:03.690
And one of them says to a
journalist, I know material

01:01:03.690 --> 01:01:07.980
about my opponent which I'm
ready to tell you if you

01:01:07.980 --> 01:01:10.820
promise me confidentiality.

01:01:10.820 --> 01:01:13.330
Really bad stuff.

01:01:13.330 --> 01:01:17.330
The journalist, a young
journalist, promised

01:01:17.330 --> 01:01:18.690
confidentiality.

01:01:18.690 --> 01:01:22.810
And he told the story of how his
opponent had been arrested

01:01:22.810 --> 01:01:28.760
as a teenager for shoplifting
in a Woolworth's store.

01:01:28.760 --> 01:01:31.660
Not much of a crime.

01:01:31.660 --> 01:01:35.900
She goes back to her office,
and she tells her boss,

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:39.690
editor, what she's found.

01:01:39.690 --> 01:01:41.370
The editor says, that's
no story.

01:01:41.370 --> 01:01:43.000
The story is, he's

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.720
leaking this crap [LAUGHTER]

01:01:46.720 --> 01:01:49.370
FLOYD ABRAMS: So that's what
we're going to publish.

01:01:49.370 --> 01:01:53.900
And she said, but I promised
confidentiality to him.

01:01:53.900 --> 01:01:58.010
And he said, no, no, if
the story here is--

01:01:58.010 --> 01:02:00.470
that's just sort of
stuff he's saying.

01:02:00.470 --> 01:02:01.450
So they published that.

01:02:01.450 --> 01:02:05.320
The guy lost the election,
and he sued.

01:02:05.320 --> 01:02:11.500
And he said, I had a deal, a
contract-like situation with

01:02:11.500 --> 01:02:12.750
the reporter.

01:02:14.800 --> 01:02:16.410
And so the question--

01:02:16.410 --> 01:02:20.440
the issue came up to
the Supreme Court.

01:02:20.440 --> 01:02:24.370
And the court said that it would
be constitutional, it

01:02:24.370 --> 01:02:28.810
would not violate the First
Amendment, for Minnesota to

01:02:28.810 --> 01:02:33.200
allow a recovery in that
case by the candidate.

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:37.920
The press side had argued, we
were telling the truth.

01:02:37.920 --> 01:02:40.770
How can we be in trouble
by telling the truth?

01:02:40.770 --> 01:02:44.820
In libel law, you always win
if you tell the truth.

01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:48.230
And the answer was, well you
made an agreement, or at least

01:02:48.230 --> 01:02:52.200
that's what a jury found, that
you promised confidentiality,

01:02:52.200 --> 01:02:55.460
and you have to keep
the promise.

01:02:55.460 --> 01:02:55.880
Yes.

01:02:55.880 --> 01:02:57.470
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's
all we have time for.

01:02:57.470 --> 01:02:57.960
FLOYD ABRAMS: Right.

01:02:57.960 --> 01:02:59.160
Thank you all very much.

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:03.060
[CLAPPING]

